Package ConcreteDomain.AtomicTypes

Class RelativeTimePoint

  • java.lang.Object
    • ConcreteDomain.ConcreteObject
      • ConcreteDomain.AtomicObject
        • ConcreteDomain.AtomicTypes.RelativeTimePoint
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    DataObject, java.io.Serializable

    public class RelativeTimePoint
extends AtomicObject
implements java.io.Serializable
    This class represents relative time points like 10:15 or 10:15:6 (hour minute second)
    week 3 10:15 (every third day in a week, hour minute second)
    month 3 10:15 (every third month in a week, hour minute second)
    3 w 10:15 (every third week in a year, hour minute second)
    2 m 10:15 (every third month in a yead, hour minute second)
    3 m 2 d 10:15 (every third month, every second day in this month, hour minute second)
    and similar.

      • firstDateAfter

        public java.time.LocalDateTime firstDateAfter​(java.time.LocalDateTime date)
        This method computes for the relative date the first absolute date after the given date. Example: the relative date ist the begin of a lecture, say 10:15
        The absolute date is the first day of the semester. The result is then the absolute date-time of the first lecture in the semester.
        Parameters:
        date - an absolute date-time
        Returns:
        the first instance of the relative date after 'date'.

      • firstDayInWeek

        public static int[] firstDayInWeek​(int year,
                                   int week)
        The method computes for a given year and week first day in this week. The convention is: the first week in a year has week number 1, and it is the week intervalContaining more days are in the new year than in the old year.
        Parameters:
        year - a year in the Gregorian Calendar
        week - a week
        Returns:
        [year,month,day] for the first day (Monday) in the given week.
